Question: Describe a time when you had to make a difficult decision.
Original:  I remember the day my parents were divorced, and I was torn between staying with them or moving away. My mother had been in a mental health crisis, and she needed my help, but my father was also struggling with addiction. I knew that leaving my mother behind would be painful, but I also knew it was the only way out of our home.

I spent months weighing my options and trying to find a middle ground. I considered going back to my hometown, where I had grown up and loved, and staying with my father. But as time went on, I started to feel more and more conflicted. The love and support I had for my mother was gone, and the pain of losing her was overwhelming.

Ultimately, I decided to stay with my father because he was the only one who could provide him with the care and attention he needed. It meant sacrificing some of my own desires and dreams, but I knew that was what was necessary for me to move forward.

After weeks of considering this option, I made a final decision. I moved away from my hometown and stayed with my father for the rest of my life. I know that it was a difficult choice at first, but I know that it was ultimately the right one for me.

It's always important to weigh the pros and cons of making difficult decisions, even if they are tough. Sometimes it feels like we have no choice but to make choices that can hurt us, but by being honest about our feelings and taking our time to consider each option, we can make the best decision possible. In the end, the most important thing is to honor our own desires and beliefs, while still loving and supporting those we care about. That way, we can make the world a better place, no matter what path we choose. 

